entry.title: Accelerate `UTF16RagelIterator`
entry.content:
Improve caching: Due to the Ragel scanner using two different

UTF16RagelIterator objects, this frequently lead to situations where

we would call the character properties calls redundantly for the same

cursor position. Improve the caching logic to avoid that, by moving

the lookup to dereferencing time.



This leads to speedups of 1.77x vs 1.22x speed-up respectively in the

synthetic SymbolsIterator benchmark [1]:



Without [2], average of 3 runs of [1]:

21.033s vs. 17.337s = 1.21x speed-up



With [2], avg of 3 runs of [1]:

5.154s vs 3.064s = 1.68x speed-up



The difference between with [2]/without [2] is explained by the relative

amount of time that is spent in UTF16RagelIterator, which increases

after the optimizations in [2].



[1] https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/5307975

[2] https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/5317569

entry.title: DOM: Process `<meta>` tags synchronously upon insertion
entry.content:
The HTML Standard currently processes and applies *all* `` tags

synchronously upon insertion, during the node's "insertion steps"

(indirectly).



Before this CL, Chromium would process meta tags during the

post-insertion steps however, by having HTMLMetaElement::InsertedInto()

return

`InsertionNotificationRequest::kInsertionShouldCallDidNotifySubtreeInsertions`,

so that `HTMLMetaElement::DidNotifySubtreeInsertionsToDocument()` would

be called, which would process the meta tag appropriately.



This CL simplifies the meta tag processing model to process meta tags

synchronously upon insertion (i.e., `InsertedInto()`), which passes the

remaining two relevant WPTs, and aligns the Chromium with the HTML

Standard.



The observable effect of this are:

- `` tags get applied synchronously during

insertion, such that script elements inserted atomically *after* it

can observe the document's *new* referrer policy

entry.title: Remove FormTracker::ignore_control_changes_
entry.content:
This data member is used to ignore the following signals if set to true:

- TextFieldDidChange

- SelectControlDidChange

- TrackAutofilledElement



Supporting Evidence:

- We only set this member in DoFillFieldWithValue, which is responsible

for single field filling, which is similar to the multiple field

filling logic present in form filling, where we do not set this

attribute



- TextFieldDidChange is called by:

- TextInput::DidSetValueByUserEdit --> Safe

- HTMLTextAreaElement::SubtreeHasChanged: This is called when the user

edits a textarea (see references of the function) and not in an

autofill flow.



- SelectControlDidChange: Select controls cannot be filled via field

filling, and during form filling we do not set this logic.



- TrackAutofilledElement: This is called by PWM and they do not set the

member to true beforehand, the member is only set to true in

AutofillAgent::DoFillFieldWithValue right before calling

WebFormControlElement::SetAutofillValue and set to false afterwards.

Moreover, this would contradict the goal of the function.



- The logic was added in

https://chromiumcodereview.appspot.com/12260016 and was meant to fix a

mobile bug with the autofill popup. Now that the popup was replaced

with KA, the original bug is resolved without the added logic.



I also tested locally the following scenarios:

- Accepting an autocomplete suggestion

- Accepting an IBAN suggestion

- Accepting a Datalist suggestion



And all of them did not trigger any of the first three signals mentioned

in the beginning of this CL description.

entry.title: LoadingPredictor: Add UKM for number of OptimizationGuide predictions used for low-priority subresources
entry.content:
The existing metric counts the number of high priority subresource

loads that match the prediction. The new metric counts the number low

priority subresources (including subresources that get loaded after

the load event is dispatched). See the bug for more details.



To record this metric, this CL refactors the following:



1) Delays the recording of LoadingPredictor UKM metrics to when the

page is destroyed (instead of when the page finishes loading).

2) Change PageRequestSummary to store low priority subresource

urls/origins separately. PageRequestSummary also needed updates to

handle being kept alive past the document load.

entry.title: [ios] Convert imports to use relative path in generated header
entry.content:
When the Swift compiler generates an #import line in the generated

Objective-C header, it does not really know what include directory

path will be used by the code importing the header, so it uses

absolute paths (which bypass the issue).



The distributed compilers used by Chromium (i.e. reclient and siso)

expect all paths to be relative to the source directory (thus the

sdk/xcode_links in the build directory).



Since by convention all path in Chromium are built with at minima

`-Igen -I../..`, convert all imports in generated headers to be

relative to either directories.



Note: most of the arguments for build/toolchain/ios/swiftc.py

are changed from -$argument to --$argument as the former caused

issues as -gen-dir clashed with -Igen due to how argparse works.



Keep only arguments coming from cflags, swiftflags, ... to use

the -$argument form, and convert all the other to --$argument.

This should limit the risk of incorrectly parsing the command

line.

entry.title: [//gpu] ClientSI: Store whether client-side native buffer was used
entry.content:
This CL adds state to ClientSharedImage to have it store whether a

client-side native buffer was used in creating the service-side

SharedImage backing this ClientSharedImage. This will always be true if

the ClientSharedImage is passed in a GMBHandle to a native buffer in

its constructor. Otherwise, the creator of this ClientSharedImage must

explicitly specify the GMB type used when a client-side GMB was passed

in the creation of the SharedImage (this is the case for creation of a

entry.title: PA: Update the header paths in //base
entry.content:
Replaces "base/allocator/partition_allocator/src/partition_alloc/"

with "partition_alloc/" of header paths.



Except for the change in //base/DEPS, there are only mechanical

rewriting in other files:



```

sed -E -i 's|#include "base/allocator/partition_allocator/src/|#include "|'

```



and "git cl format".



[Background Context]

PartitionAlloc library is developed in

//base/allocator/partition_allocator/ in Chromium repo and exported

to PartitionAlloc repo from there.



Client applications are expected to import the PA lib to somewhere

they want (e.g. foo/bar) and set the include_dir appropriately

(e.g. -Ifoo/bar/src) so that `#include "partition_alloc/..."` works.



Issue 40276913 has done this setup and the PA lib is read to be used

in the way above. Now all the application projects should be rewritten

to `#include "partition_alloc/..."`.



Chromium project is a hosting project of PartitionAlloc, but it's also

a client application, too. So, we'd like to rewrite the header paths

in Chromium, too.



This patch rewrites only //base. Other directories will be rewritten

in follow-up patches.

entry.title: mojo: Implement predictive allocation (under flag)
entry.content:
Currently, Mojo progressively expands the message buffer while

serializing complex structs with multiple fields or collections of

dynamic size. In the worst case, this can cause one additional

allocation per element, collectively building up to about half the cost

of the IPC for particularly complex messages.



This change implements a mechanism to track the per-message history of

previous allocations to inform subsequent allocations. For now, this

logic needs to be enabled on a per-message basis.



Design doc: http://go/predictive-mojo-allocation

entry.title: Revert "webnn: Enable TFLite-based WebNN service on Android and ChromeOS"
entry.content:
This reverts commit a21a9c6f0399a795a349ecbb26fe12f71cf40ab8.



Reason for revert:

LUCI Bisection has identified this change as the cause of a test failure. See the analysis: https://ci.chromium.org/ui/p/chromium/bisection/test-analysis/b/5691047629815808



Sample build with failed test: https://ci.chromium.org/b/8753529111454693537

Affected test(s):

[ninja://third_party/blink/renderer/controller:blink_unittests/MLGraphXnnpackTest.EluTest/All.Xnnpack](https://ci.chromium.org/ui/test/chromium/ninja:%2F%2Fthird_party%2Fblink%2Frenderer%2Fcontroller:blink_unittests%2FMLGraphXnnpackTest.EluTest%2FAll.Xnnpack?q=VHash%3A72131c834bfd2078)



If this is a false positive, please report it at http://b.corp.google.com/createIssue?component=1199205&description=Analysis%3A+https%3A%2F%2Fci.chromium.org%2Fui%2Fp%2Fchromium%2Fbisection%2Ftest-analysis%2Fb%2F5691047629815808&format=PLAIN&priority=P3&title=Wrongly+blamed+https%3A%2F%2Fchromium-review.googlesource.com%2Fc%2Fchromium%2Fsrc%2F%2B%2F5368950&type=BUG



Original change's description:

> webnn: Enable TFLite-based WebNN service on Android and ChromeOS

>

> This change expands the usage of the TFLite-based WebNN service

> implementation from Linux-only to Android and ChromeOS as well.

>

> Enabling it on Android is a necessary step for issue 41486052, which

> will leverage Android-specific TFLite delegates to access mobile ML

> accelerator hardware. As expected since this is the first change to

> enable a functional end-to-end implementation of WebNN there is a small

> binary size impact. About half of this is the Mojo bindings and the

> other is the graph validation and TFLite flatbuffer construction code.

> This is largely unavoidable. The bulk of the binary size cost has

> already been borne by the other Chrome features which originally

> introduced the TFLite dependency.

>

> Enabling it on ChromeOS is a necessary step for issue 326356909 however

> as currently implemented the instance of TFLite in the browser process

entry.title: [Office upload] Always interpret empty user dialog response as a cancel
entry.content:
Previously, an empty user response to a setup flow, move confirmation or

fallback dialog was not expected (with one handled exception). However,

this can occur when the user logs out of the session and the dialog is

unexpectedly closed. This led to the TaskResult not being logged.



Update the code to always map an empty user response to a Cancel user

choice. Leave an error log behind as there could be other undiagnosed

causes to an empty user response.
